   "source": [
    "# Phase 2: Upgrading to a State-of-the-Art Vision Transformer\n",
    "---\n",
    "## 🌟 Why are we doing this? (For Recruiters!)\n",
    "In Phase 1, we built a `CNN + LSTM` model from scratch. That showed we know the **fundamentals** of Deep Learning.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, in the real world, companies don't usually build models from scratch because it takes too much time and data. Instead, they take massive, powerful models built by companies like Google or Meta, and use them directly. This is called **Transfer Learning**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we are upgrading our app to use **VideoMAE**, a highly advanced Vision Transformer.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 💡 Do we need to train this model on our data?\n",
    "**NO!** That is the magic of this approach. This specific model (`MCG-NJU/videomae-base-finetuned-kinetics`) has already been trained on the **Kinetics-400 dataset** (a massive dataset of 300,000+ videos). \n",
    "\n",
    "It already knows how to recognize **400 different human actions** perfectly out of the box. We just plug it in and let it do the work! We do not need to retrain it on our old dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 1: Install the Required Tools\n",
    "We need a few tools to make this work. Even if you only know TensorFlow, don't worry! We are using **Hugging Face (`transformers`)**, which is an incredible library that makes using AI models as easy as writing 3 lines of code. It uses PyTorch under the hood, but you don't need to write any PyTorch code yourself."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Install transformers (Hugging Face's library for AI models)\n",
    "# Install torch (PyTorch, the engine running our AI. Hugging Face uses it behind the scenes)\n",
    "# Install opencv-python and av (For handling video files)\n",
    "!pip install -q transformers torch opencv-python av"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 2: Import our Libraries\n",
    "Let's bring in the tools we just installed so our Python code can use them."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import torch # The core machine learning engine\n",
    "from transformers import pipeline # The 'magic wand' that loads pre-trained AI models easily\n",
    "import time # To track how long the AI takes to think"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 3: Load the AI Model 🧠\n",
    "Here, we load our pre-trained Vision Transformer. \n",
    "\n",
    "In the past (with your CNN+LSTM), you had to manually extract frames from a video, resize them, normalize the pixels, and feed them into a model. Hugging Face's `pipeline` function does **all of this automatically for us**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"Loading the Vision Transformer. Please wait...\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# STEP A: Check if we have a powerful Graphics Card (GPU)\n",
    "# If we have a GPU (CUDA), torch.cuda.is_available() is True, so we use device = 0.\n",
    "# If we don't have a GPU, we use device = -1, which tells it to run on the normal CPU.\n",
    "device = 0 if torch.cuda.is_available() else -1\n",
    "\n",
    "# STEP B: Create the Pipeline\n",
    "# We tell it we want to do 'video-classification'.\n",
    "# We give it the name of the pre-trained model we want to download from the internet.\n",
    "video_pipeline = pipeline(\n",
    "    task=\"video-classification\", \n",
    "    model=\"MCG-NJU/videomae-base-finetuned-kinetics\",\n",
    "    device=device\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"✅ Model loaded and ready to recognize videos!\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 4: Create our Video Analysis Function 🎥\n",
    "Now we write a simple function that takes a video file, gives it to the AI, and prints out what the AI saw. Every line is commented so you know exactly what is happening."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def analyze_my_video(video_file_path):\n",
    "    print(f\"\\n🔍 Looking at your video: {video_file_path}\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Start a stopwatch to see how fast the AI is\n",
    "    start_time = time.time()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # --- THE MAGIC HAPPENS HERE ---\n",
    "    # We literally just pass the video path to our pipeline.\n",
    "    # top_k=3 means we want the AI's top 3 best guesses.\n",
    "    ai_guesses = video_pipeline(video_file_path, top_k=3)\n",
    "    # ------------------------------\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Stop the stopwatch and calculate how long it took\n",
    "    time_taken = time.time() - start_time\n",
    "    print(f\"⏱️ Analysis finished in {time_taken:.2f} seconds!\\n\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(\"Here is what the AI thinks is happening in the video:\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # The AI returns a list of guesses. Let's loop through them one by one.\n",
    "    # 'enumerate' just gives us a counter (i) so we can number them 1, 2, 3.\n",
    "    for i, guess in enumerate(ai_guesses):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # The label comes out looking like 'playing_basketball'.\n",
    "        # Let's clean it up to look like 'Playing Basketball'.\n",
    "        raw_label = guess['label']\n",
    "        clean_label = raw_label.replace('_', ' ').title()\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # The score is a decimal like 0.95. Let's multiply by 100 to make it a percentage (95%).\n",
    "        confidence_percentage = guess['score'] * 100\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Print the final result beautifully!\n",
    "        # f-strings let us put variables directly inside the text using {}\n",
    "        print(f\"  {i+1}. {clean_label} (Confidence: {confidence_percentage:.1f}%)\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 5: Let's Test It! 🚀\n",
    "Find a video in your project folder, change the path below, and run the cell!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Point this to any video in your 'Sample_Videos' folder or anywhere else.\n",
    "# Make sure to put the correct path to an actual video on your computer!\n",
    "my_test_video = \"Sample_Videos/sample_1.mp4\"\n",
    "\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    # Call our function\n",
    "    analyze_my_video(my_test_video)\n",
    "except Exception as error:\n",
    "    # If something goes wrong (like the video file doesn't exist), print a helpful error message.\n",
    "    print(\"❌ Oops! Something went wrong.\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Error details: {error}\")\n",
    "    print(\"\\nDid you make sure 'sample_1.mp4' actually exists in the 'Sample_Videos' folder?\")"
   ]
  }
